Resolved on 2026-05-11

1. Issue: In the restock workflow, when a supplier is created, initially even when you add a re-order schedule it doesn't actually get updated to the database, it only successfully updates when you afterward edit and update the supplier.
   Resolution: Updated the create supplier server action to persist reorder schedule fields during initial insert, including schedule type, start date, custom dates, recurring flag, and schedule notes. Also updated the supplier create form reset state so new supplier forms consistently include the schedule fields.
   How to verify: In Admin > Restock > Manage Suppliers, add a new supplier with a re-order schedule before saving. After the supplier is created, confirm the supplier card immediately displays the schedule and the supplier row in the database includes the reorder_schedule_* values without requiring an edit-and-save.

2. Issue: All of the numerical input fields in the restock pages and components are of a type that is not user friendly, it's the type that lets you increase or decrease the value with the arrow keys, however that is not the type that we want, that type makes it difficult to change the value and difficult to delete a single digit, change all of them to a more input friendly type and we don't need to use the arrow keys to increase or decrease the values.
   Resolution: Replaced the restock workflow number inputs with text inputs that use numeric/decimal input modes and validation patterns. Updated the affected change handlers so empty fields can remain empty while editing instead of immediately snapping back to default values, which makes deleting/replacing individual digits easier.
   How to verify: Run `rg -n "type=\"number\"|type='number'" components/admin/restock app/admin/restock` and confirm no matches are returned. In the restock UI, edit quantities, lead time, minimum order amount, supplier unit price, minimum order quantity, and received quantity; each field should allow normal text-style editing with no browser spinner controls.

3. Issue: TypeScript reports that compiler option `baseUrl` is deprecated and will stop functioning in TypeScript 7.0 unless `ignoreDeprecations` is set.
   Resolution: Removed the deprecated `baseUrl` compiler option from `tsconfig.json`; the existing alias path remains relative (`"@/*": ["./*"]`) and no longer depends on the deprecated option.
   How to verify: Run `npx tsc --noEmit --pretty false` and confirm the previous `baseUrl` deprecation diagnostic is not reported.
